<TITLE> Swiss players moving abroad too early, says Hitzfeld </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 VIENNA, Sept 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Switzerland are paying a price for losing too many young players to foreign leagues, national coach Ottmar Hitzfeld said on Tuesday. "It is good to have players with experience on a European level but too many Swiss youngsters are leaving the country too early," the 59-year-old told the UEFA Conference for European National Coaches. "They sign with big clubs and then sit on the bench. But you cannot earn match practice from being a substitute," added the German. Switzerland suffered a humiliating 2-1 home defeat by tiny Luxembourg in a 2010 World Cup qualifier this month and are fifth out of six teams in Group Two, with only Moldova beneath them. Despite the shocking result, and howls of criticism in the Swiss media, Hitzfeld said he was happy being a national coach and did not envy his club successor Juergen Klinsmann at Bayern Munich. "When I saw Bayern Munich lose 5-2 (at home to Werder Bremen) last weekend I was relieved not to have the same pressure of being a club manager anymore," he said. "Even a draw is basically a defeat for the Bayern bosses," he added. "Considering my age, this was one of the main reasons, why I decided to move to national team level. "I only get to see my players for a couple of days each month or maybe not even that," laughed Hitzfeld. "Actually, coaching a national team is an adventure, nearly frivolous.
